# Product Ethics — UI & Frontend Checks

When writing or reviewing UI components, apply these checks before completing any implementation.

## Accessibility (Foundational)
- [ ] Interactive elements are keyboard-navigable (focus states visible, tab order logical)
- [ ] Images have descriptive `alt` text; decorative images have `alt=""`
- [ ] Color is never the sole means of conveying information (add icon, text, or pattern)
- [ ] Text contrast meets WCAG 2.1 AA minimum (4.5:1 body, 3:1 large text)
- [ ] Motion and animation respect `prefers-reduced-motion`
- [ ] Form inputs have associated `<label>` elements, not just placeholder text
- [ ] Error messages are specific, visible, and not color-only
- [ ] Touch targets are at least 44x44px

## Representation & Stigma (Structural)
- [ ] Illustrations, avatars, and example content represent demographic diversity — not as decoration but as default
- [ ] Form fields don't assume binary gender, Western name format, or nuclear family structure unless legally required
- [ ] UI copy doesn't use stigmatizing, pathologizing, or dehumanizing language
- [ ] Generated or stock imagery has been checked for demographic default bias

## Dark Patterns / Honesty (Foundational)
- [ ] No confirmshaming ("No thanks, I don't want to save money")
- [ ] No artificial urgency (countdown timers that reset, manufactured scarcity)
- [ ] Destructive or irreversible actions require explicit confirmation
- [ ] Privacy-protective choices are at least as prominent as permissive choices
- [ ] Cancellation / opt-out flows are as simple as sign-up / opt-in flows

## Autonomy & Defaults (Structural)
- [ ] Default settings serve the user's interest, not the platform's
- [ ] Every significant default can be documented with a user-interest rationale
- [ ] Users can discover and change defaults without expert navigation

## User Health (Foundational — if engagement features present)
- [ ] No infinite scroll without a visible stopping point or user-controlled pagination
- [ ] Notification logic is triggered by user value, not re-engagement optimization
- [ ] Streak or reward mechanics don't generate loss aversion as a primary driver
- [ ] Usage time indicators or break prompts are present if session length is a metric

## AI-Generated Content (Foundational — if applicable)
- [ ] AI-generated text, images, audio, or video is labeled as such
- [ ] Users can distinguish AI responses from human responses

**Raise before shipping:** If any check cannot be confirmed, raise it as a concern in the PR or design review. Do not mark "to be addressed later" without a linked issue and milestone.
